The Ukrainian Parliament refused, in the context of an amendment to criminal law, the draft annulment of the paragraph on the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
The members of Parliament rejected in second reading the proposed amendment to reduce penalties for economic offences, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for having entered into a previously detrimental agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not final and the court is to decide on the appeal of the convicted person in December.
Tymosenko qualifies the political revenge judgement of the regime and has caused a process of suspicions of bias of the court also to the west.
The draft annulment of paragraph 365 of criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was sentenced, was signed by 147 Members.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve.
