Feeding an obese child: don't have breakfast and take the charcuterie for dinner
More than one third of 9-13-year-olds have overweight problems, 9% of schoolchildren will weigh above average and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families that have an unhealthy lifestyle.
This shows again how important is the environment in which the human being and the models around it evolve.
On the tables of obese children, for example, 50% carcuterie is found more often than in families of children with normal weight.
19% of the obese had dinner fries according to the survey conducted with an awareness action "Obesity is not a chance"
In small-sized families sport is also not a habit, which is now the case of most schoolchildren today - only 15% responded that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place during the last school year and attended 900 students from primary schools in Chechnya.
It was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence," supported by General Health Insurance and Unilever.
Since the beginning, more than 12000 sixth to third students have enrolled in this project.
One of the determining factors that causes a dramatic increase in the number of overweight or even obese children is the absence of a proper diet and not enough physical exercise.
"Only half of the children asked indicate, for example, eating 5 times a day breakfast-in case - lunch-taste- dinner, which is a basic principle of good food," says one of the results of the survey.
Without breakfast and dinner charcuterie
Specialists draw attention to the fact that healthy development requires some basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In Chechnya, only 23% of students' families eat at the same time.
In most families each has his own breakfast.
And the worst thing is that one tenth of the population don't have breakfast at all.
Yet breakfast is the basis of good daily food.
The questionnaire showed that in families of obese children, unhealthy fries are consumed more often.
Almost every student - not to mention the weight - drinks sweet drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of the children asked do sports regularly, but for parents it is only half, 15%.
Prepare Your Food
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own food on the basis of opportunities offered according to their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children between 12 and 15 years of age are far from ideal in terms of healthy diet."
Among their favorite dishes are many cakes, meats and sugars.
"The most alarming is particularly a preference for sweet lemonades," is indicated in the results of the survey.
For lunch are the pasta that took the first place right in front of the white meat.
Children did not want to be fertilized at all, and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Health heading
The survey also showed that children are ready to change their habits as soon as they receive ad hoc information.
"In the course of a review of a group of survey participants who had completed the questionnaire after the awareness-raising session "Obesity is not a coincidence," a strong commitment was made to a healthy diet," the results of the survey indicated.
The most significant was, for example, for sweet lemonades, as children began to give preference to drinking water.
Children have usually checked on the questionnaire white meat and fish as the main dish and would reduce sweet dishes and "knedliky" (Czech speciality of breadmeal or potatoes).
