How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered trips especially in the countries of the socialist bloc, because travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have a inclination for the west and trips to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not authorized for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovakians) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
If the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example in Poland or in the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter or the individual travel was not permitted.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the west, however, it was necessary to make the queue all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it wasn't yet won.
The currency agreement which was the condition for traveling to the west was denied to the "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not interchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the currency agreement (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs spent most of their vacations in the country where there were therefore many country houses and cottages that Czechs bought and this habit lasts so far.
Czech travel has since experienced a great revolution since 1989.
Although up to 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were maximum, Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million vacation days in countries around the world.
The great paradox we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because part of Yugoslavia of the time.
The removal of visas in the 1990s in the neighbouring western countries caused a huge wave of short-term visits especially in Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks were not able to travel by plane for a long time to the west that everyone wanted to see for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations made Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our incomes did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a Czech trip was at that time to take his own canned food, sausage, etc... to save money.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown which finally allowed our tourists after decades of freely buying Western currency.
Our standard of living and the average wage have increased what has caused another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to a growing demand for travel, travel agencies have since 1997 started to prepare tours with air charter links that through contracts have dramatically reduced costs compared to what was before.
At the end of the 1990s, Czechs had visa-free links with virtually most developed countries around the world except the EU that later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year and every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to the distant warm countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
It is more than 100,000 Czechs who visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development came in 2008.
on 17 November 2008, the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to settle completely in the group of developed countries.
In 2008, Czechs also spent the first time in history more than half of their vacation abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15,000 krona per person for vacation abroad, including the attached charges.
