21st house in Vienna
The Pavilion That Moved
D'Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with tops, bottoms and a Happy End: the Austrian flag for the world exhibitions of Brussels in 1958 won prizes, it was a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then collapsed.
Now it's open again and takes place as an exhibition house.
If you are excited about a modern post-war architecture, its clear forms, its glass hangars, its lively and bold features and its new construction materials that are typical of belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of Austrian architect Karl Schwanzer for the universal exhibition of Brussels in 1958 is a good and famous example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion once received the "Grand Prix d'Architecture" for its steel and glass construction, light and suspended.
Construction is considered to be an important step in contemporary architecture to date.
He made the architects so famous, that he also built the Pavilion for the next Austrian universal exhibition.
With its legendary four-cylinder BMW house and its adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it eventually became internationally famous in 1973.
His project of pavilion as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the universal exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the station south of Vienna, was transformed, and in 1962 a 20th-century museum opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to hang the works of art, so not a good environment.
However, it has been used for so long, until contemporary art receives a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and increasingly weakened.
Now architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, he now bears the name "House of the 21st Century" and will be in the future used as a museum for contemporary art.
Tuesday evening the Belvedère Museum opened, to which the house belongs, the first exhibition - a chance shot at all points of view.
The new departure was completed by Agnès Husslein-Arco, who became the new director in 2007 of the Austrian gallery Belvedère.
Husslein-Arco has promoted an art historian to a considerable career, among others, in his youth as an artistic skater, subsequently at Sotheby's, at the Guggenheim Museum and as founder of the modern art museum in Salzburg, she has carried out particularly well the transformation work with political men and the protection of monuments, she has obtained public funds and private sponsorship and has established its exploitation.
Except for contemporary art, the works of sculptor Fritz Wotruba whose foundation bears the same name have been exposed, a coffee shop and a bookstore are there, and an office must be built there.
Strict monitoring, small budget
For Krischanitz was therefore the ideal interpreter.
Not only because he had transformed and expanded with sensitivity Joseph Olbracht's secession and won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and because for him the pavilion was "an extremely important place" where he had seen "almost every weekend" exhibitions.
He knew the project of origin, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost generosity and lightness as a result of its move to Vienna and its change of use.
During the current transformations, there were major problems: the building was "a gouffre in energy," said Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass façades were changed, the glass insulating reinforced glass fibers was placed and the roof replaced by a particular safety glass.
The thermal bridges were reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled coatings were rehabilitated.
Two basements have made room for the new operation, a panel of closed light between the house and the road ensures lighting, a bridge led to the entrance - it is almost a new construction, but always the light Pavillon Schwanzer.
The exterior doors of origin have remained, the house is painted in a shade protection against red-brown rust.
And the cinema is even exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under close supervision by the competent authorities for monuments and with a small budget.
"S often materials that are good and inexpensive should be found, and which also please the Office of Protection Monuments," said Krishnatz, and he draws attention to a gross ground in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and transformations, the building remained flexible and light.
This would have been difficult with the Pavillon, "which came from Brussels," said Krischanitz recently, a typical story of "Drop-in-the-City".
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken the good conscience".
But in this case the House of the 21st century is not in the wrong place, because if it is a chance of urban construction: around the Swiss Garden stands precisely the "quarter of the central station" newly planned, with offices and apartments.
And another chance will perhaps occur: the House of the 21st century could benefit from the reinforcement of another Krischanitz construction, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg purchased the Berlin temporary art centre, and as it is said, she already negotiates with the city to obtain a site in the vicinity of the Swiss Garden.
