But what Apple fans can find more revealing in a recently found Steve Jobs interview that will be broadcast this week in the first part of a film on the main markets, is how creative this spirit understood the processes and workflows of products.
He was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer. He was identified with a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as an improved organizational chart - a man who believed that many business leaders were suffering from a "disease letting them think that a brilliant idea makes 90% of the work... [but] a considerable amount of manual work separates a brilliant idea from an exceptional product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series "Triumph of the Nerds". This series portrays the birth of the computer, and he sits for more than an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
At that time, it was about 10 years ago that Steve Jobs had had to leave Apple. He was already working hard on his new NeXT computer company, aimed at popular Internet adoption.
While a small part of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he states that the main copies have disappeared in transportation.
It was only after Steve Jobs died that a full video was found in the director's garage.
This video, slightly remounted, is the basis of the 68-minute film entitled Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will be broadcast at the cinema Wednesday and Thursday next.
For someone known to hate deep-seated interviews, Steve Jobs seems amazingly enthusiastic here to expose technological philosophies and its business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts, in order to provide a precise answer.
There are also moments when Steve Jobs' perfectionism rises, where he seems to be looking forward to hearing Cringely's questions, kicking him to speed him up and move on to more important questions or subjects.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, we find a strange aspect of Lost Interview. Steve Jobs evaluates what he considers good or bad in other companies and reports his own vision of the future of computer science.
It is one thing to read Steve Jobs' posthumous evaluations of career, but there is something gross and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can be and must be.
He explains them and then implements them.
Here is a quick summary of seven outstanding sequences of Lost Interview:
On how he learned to run a business:
"During all these years, I have always asked: 'Why do you do things?' and the answers are constantly the same: 'Oh, just because you have to do them.'
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a business.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs continues to provide details on his efforts to simplify Apple's accounting.
Perplexed about how the costs were recorded - we often start with a "standard cost" evaluated for nose, then adjusted with a "variation" - it developed an automated factory that ensured the precise calculation of commercial costs.
On the opportunity to play a tour of the Pope:
Steve Jobs relates the anecdote of the "Bleu Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that used to hack telephone networks and phone for free in long distance.
The device has been written many times before, but Steve Jobs' euphoria here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public phone, passing a call then connecting from an AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
"We wrapped up the ball of different things a half a dozen times and you screamed on the public phone and it would come to you a minute later on the public phone next door," explains Jobs laughing.
"We were young and thanks to this Blue Box, we learned that we could create something that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world."
We didn't know much, but we were able to invent a small thing capable of controlling great things. It was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would ever exist without that.
Steve Jobs continues by telling a wonderful tour that he and Wozniak have developed: he telephoned the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night and turned to Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are called in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices go mad to laugh just before the Pope himself is awake.
On his love of technology (and departure of Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to manufacture a frequency meter, he looks for Bill Hewlett's number in the directory and passes him a wire.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs gets a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable influence on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it formed my definition of a company and how employees are treated."
Steve Jobs later became one of the HP employees to visit the company's research laboratories, located in Palo Alto, where he discovered the "first ever designed desktop computer."
He was as big as a suitcase, had a little cathode tube. I fell in love with him.
The teenager I was returning to HP and began writing programs for this machine.
On the improvisation of innovation:
At several moments in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products on a head shot.
At the beginning of his career, while he moved in to sell some printed circuit board, a client asked him to assemble a complete computer.
Working at only 30 days' credit, he should take care of the assembly and delivery of the finished equipment.
Later, in Apple, he recalled the difficulties encountered in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember the big fights... they shouted at me, claiming it took me five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300]. I had enough, I got out and went to see a designer."
Eighty days later, we had a mouse that we could make for $15 and that was incredibly reliable.
On large companies that are experiencing:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated how many industrial leaders were going to cheat and lose control of their market share.
"Let's admit that you worked at IBM or Xerox, you make a better copyr or a better printer, and then?"
You have the monopoly of the market, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing can evolve, so [these are these types of people] that end up leading companies and specialized product personnel are set aside from decision-making.
The product engineering that led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by people who cannot imagine designing a good product compared to a bad product - the manual work required.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
She could have made her current size ten times. Xerox would have been Microsoft in the 1990s...
They took the defeat to victory.
On innovation as an artistic form:
"A huge piece of manual work separates a great idea from an exceptional product... as you develop this idea, it changes and grows."
You learn a lot about his subtleties.
There are compromises to do... some things you can't do, electrons can, glass, robots, factories too.
You must keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) by assembling them to each other.
Finally, decisions are made by personal taste. It is about trying to expose you to the best products that men have created, and trying to bring these things to the product you create.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and that great artists fly.
We are always ashamed to steal excellent ideas.
It is in part what makes Macintosh exceptional. The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who simply proved themselves the best computer scientists in the world.
If it were not for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another area.
