How to spot a lie
A look at recent headlines indicates the extent to which deception and lies are omnipresent in everyday life.
The Republican candidate for President Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accused the other of lying.
Penn State administrators were accused of having allegedly covered reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was taken by an open voice saying to American President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
The member of the New York Congress and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner, went on to be an idiot by quickly emitting contradictions contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
The former presidential candidate John Edwards was accused of violations of the funding of campaigns related to the coverage of an extra-conjugal link.
And then none of those who have experienced history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered by lying during his second term on his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating on school and university tests are legion.
There have been cases where teachers have given the test answers to students to make themselves aware of their performance assessments.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send the message that lies and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we encounter?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear from 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are lousy lies.
Another study showed that foreigners lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their meeting.
Detecting or detecting lies is an essential competence that each one must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a game of society similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to write: "I've had you," the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities that have conducted a thorough research of such projects, including psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lies have been demystified.
The liars look into your eyes.
They don't drink, they pray or they don't always get upset.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to expose.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial micro-expressions, the formation of the question and the time of response.
I have spent several years examining scientific results in the vast body and always emerging from knowledge about deception, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful to navigate into our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include employment, interviews, negotiation or management.
Good liars are skilled at reading the others, putting them at ease, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extraverts lie more than introverts, than men say more lies "focused on them" while women say more lies "focused on others" - usually to protect someone's feelings - than married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell tend to be enormous).
We also know that if you are perceived as a believer, the others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How can you say if someone's lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
That's what we call "setting the benchmark data."
This helps to provide a benchmark to measure subsequent changes.
Look at the posture of your subject, laughter, vocal quality.
You need to know if someone normally stirs his feet permanently so as not to launch unjust accusations when you see him stir his feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then search for hints of verbal and nonverbal misleading behaviour.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceiving people can immobilize the top of the body when they try to remember their history, they can point their feet towards the door, lean towards a exit, change their posture significantly or present a relief of "post-interview" - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all difficult questions are passed.
The interviewers often falsely indicate that the interview was completed just to seek to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson deraped using the past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Deceptive individuals can also use a distant language: "I have not had sexual relations with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or completely repeat a difficult question.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wood language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell you the truth... if I remember well... to my knowledge."
This makes the perception response rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for the detection of lies, but the development of skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone avoiding victimization by hijackers in their professional and personal lives.
