According to the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development's ice-cream allocations report, there were 582 million 835 hectares of crops, of which 78.03 per cent suffered total damage and the rest of 21.07 per cent suffered partial damage, the main crops were vegetables, maize and chic peas.
The decline in economic activity generated, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the State, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the rate of unemployment of the State during the first three quarters of the year was seen to be accelerated, as during January to March 55 thousand 053 signals were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the Active Economic Population, the rate in the second quarter became 5.28 per cent and July to September the average continued to rise to 6.19 per cent, a rate representing more than 74 thousand unemployed signals, an increase compared to the first half of 18 thousand 969 persons.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly by public policy actions.
"What is observed is an increase in unemployment due to various factors, including the loss of liquidity on the market due to a restriction of resources under the legislation approved in Congress to combat money-laundering, because for people who make dollars in an illegal way it is not easy for them to work to gain them, invest them and use them in something," he said.
Migration held
López Cervantes reported that the rise in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the State to go to work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties of entry and second because they already have a lot of difficulty in finding work, these people remain here and ask for sources of work, which makes unemployment rising," he said.
Lack of serious
According to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the population employed in this state is working there without contributing as a worker to any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and the lack of serious benefits, another reason for dislocation for the state is low wages, the entity has lower remuneration in the country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Forecast.
The average monthly income of signal workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, much less than the national average, which is 7 thousand 375 pesos.
FDI Contraction
Apart from the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, the highest reduction in the Foreign Direct Investment in 2011 over the past 10 years was recorded, according to the Economic Secretariat from January to June, the State FDI reached $630 thousand 697, representing a decrease of 87.74 per cent compared to the $5 million 143 thousand 312 recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Economic Development Secretariat of the Government of the State accounts for a total investment of 17,280 billion pesos per year, mainly registered by the tertiary sector companies.
Debt
Given the economic contraction scenario, the Government of the State in July called for approval of a 3 billion pesos credit for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, the approval of the state congress was 2.600 billion pesos and until November there was no benefit of debt in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the employer sector, the first year of Government of Mario López Valdés shows a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said in 2011 there was no harmonization of the will of the various sectors, including the Government of the State.
"The performance of the Sinaloa economy during this year has been really very poor, it is necessary to work intensively to recover the land we lost this year, in 2012 we need to double our efforts, it has been necessary to align the effort of all and above all the good already synchronized walk of this new government team, let's hope that next year is much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López stated that events such as the ice creams of the beginning of the year have retained the state economy and have restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is produced by several events, including ice cream, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level and flow into trials, products and services and, therefore, at the end of the year we close much below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefine vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, President of the Patronal Confederation of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa, said that we want to channel the state into productive activities of more dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that work has been done, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the State, because it is important that the full potential of the material and human resources of Sinaloa be detonated," he said.
A lot to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better channels the Government's efforts.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to achieve good results in different areas of economic development there is some progress, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in the management of public policy.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is more inclusive, what I can say is that there has been a lot of work and that the Government is aware of the fact that there is still a lot to do," he said.
