Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) rejected the constitutional disputes that the Senate and the House of Deputies have made against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analog cupure" from 2021 to 2015, as the eight votes necessary to invalidate it have not been gathered.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his duties when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to realize the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic has been rejected for failing to reach the qualified majority of eight votes so that the Court can decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the decree's declaration as non-constitutional, because radio and television regulations are a statutory award to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reserve of law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the House of Deputies have promoted two constitutional disputes to challenge the decree and admit complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions planned by it for the digital transition.
The plenary meeting of the Ministers also resolved to dismiss the complaint made by the House of Deputies, without discussing the project that Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible for.
In his speech, the Minister said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure the measures to be prepared by general standards.
"I also consider that if I did so, the autonomy of the regulatory body would be affected," and he recalled that planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, which has the constitutional mandate of the government.
The substitution of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years and this results in a better operation of the radio spectrum, better quality of the signal and more channels.
Adjournment of change, he said, would be to adjourn the benefits of digitisation which implies a decision of public interest which not only has a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues".
These questions, he stressed, "requires the operation of an entire system established, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, to include a group of powers which the Constitution grants to the power of the Executive of the State".
He recalled that a large number of countries from all over the world have already completed the digital transition and have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they had highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has invaded the sphere of competence of Congress in a form, since it ensures in the administrative sphere respect for the laws issued by the legislature, it is safe.
An analysis of the possibility of a vote-by-vote count in Michoacán
According to the data highlighted by PREP, the difference between the first and second place of the Governor's election is only 27 per cent, even without accounting for the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
The possibility of the "vote by vote" bill is a reality with regard to the electoral trial this year in Michoacán, where according to the data highlighted by the Preliminary Election Results Program (PREP) the difference between the first and second place of the Governor's election is only 27 percent, even without accounting for the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
In this regard, the President of the General Council of the Institut Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards with federal electoral reform.
It will be recalled that Michoacán has not approved its Political Constitution or its Electoral Code of State or its Electoral Justice Act, while the Congress of the State has approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for this election to come into force and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel has omitted his publication within the time frame provided for by the Law of the Official Journal of the State, with the argument that he had a few objections.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the Local Legislative Power and qualified as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the state's representative for constitutional reforms, as he does not have the right to "sanction or challenge them".
Interviewed on the possibility of the "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal said that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of EMI it will be possible to carry out the partial and total counts of the votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial count of votes, one or more electoral packages, may be that: the results of the minutes do not match; there is no vote minutes and the vote records in the ballot file are not in the President's office; or there are obvious errors or alterations in the minutes.
In addition, the total count of votes received in all polls of the election may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the supposed candidate winning the respective election and the one who obtained the second place in the poll is equal to or below a percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition by the party's representative and/or coalition that presented the second one of the candidates reported.
The total voter's account may also be held if at the end of the joint account it turns out that the difference between the supposed winning candidate and that of the second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is a express petition by the representative of the political party whose candidate has emerged second, in which case the electoral packages that were subject to the partial counting will be excluded.
It should be noted that this is the situation of the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without accounting for the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
