The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The designated Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put that country on the brink of the economic disaster
The designated Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet on Wednesday with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of the economic disaster and threatened the entire Eurozone.
A press release from the Presidential Palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet on Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he can form the Government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed of technocrats in his majority, even if it is not clear when the new executive will assume his position.
Monti said he was going to present to the president the outcome of his talks with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," said the former European Commissioner for Journalists.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government, but his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The "frame is now well-drawn," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than normally, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has raised its debt costs to levels that cannot be supported.
The new administration led by the former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package required by European leaders to regain confidence in Italy that had been affected.
By stressing the pressure on Monti to hurry, the instability of the markets to place the performance of the Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 per cent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian patronal Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government a lot."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to emerge from this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were greatly stimulated by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, to which the crisis forced to resign last Saturday.
"We believe Professor Monti's efforts will have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the right-wing party, told the press.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because so far many of its members have opposed the Government of the technocrat majority that Monti forms.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what is likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or delay in its efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks has added to the pressure by observing that a failure of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations with political parties, trade unions and employers' groups and youth and women's organizations on Monday.
He'll finish his meeting tour Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief burst at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi was going to resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels of uncertainty about the success of the new Prime Minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 billion euros, would be too much for the current financial defences of Eurozone.
Monti said that his Government should continue until future elections, planned for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians would only give it time to implement reforms before the elections were made.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his office, but the big parties insist that it should only be trained by specialists, an index of their objections to a process driven by financial pressure.
Political sources have reported that mutual mistrust and disagreement between parties complicate the attempt to include political figures.
