After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Sports Independence Unit (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Sports Morelos Unit (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and the objective of this investigation is to identify the components and the importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in children and young Mexicans to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
As will be celebrated on 14 November on World Diabetes Day, he noted that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14 with the consent and supervision of their parents for the application of specific feeding questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and history of family inheritance of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that Saturdays will be applied to all participants in anthropometric measurements (weight, size, size, circumference of the size), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetic levels (to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of health professionals' concern about alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that, in just six years, there was an increase of 77 per cent in obesity among boys and 47 per cent of girls; there was also a dramatic increase in overweight,' said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from the others by its genetic history.
He informed that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent indo-American inheritance, 30 percent in Europe and five percent in Africa, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, obesity genetics translates into the inability to burn the excess energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the full evaluation of children, which enables them to detect if they have an excess or obesity level.
He even said that the presence of dark-colored folds (canthosis) on the neck and forearms indicate the probability of having metabolic and even pre-diabetes alterations.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, and doctors write it to their parents, each of whom explains the measures and changes in the lifestyle they need to carry out in order to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentarism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, to stay most of the day sitting on TV and to use means of transport instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is the high calorie intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sweet drinks, carbohydrates (tamals - meat pasta to cornmeal wrapped in corn leaves - bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM's asphalt would avoid cassis
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs that the pavement was resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair approximately 200 thousand rainfalls each rainy season in the Métropolitaine Area of Valle de México, alert Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who ensured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bituminous pavement is adequate, the cassis could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A technological opinion on cassis, organized within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the performance, and therefore the formation of cassis.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphalts, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, almost 180 degrees, behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes broken, added.
This means that in the streets asphalt resistance is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineering specialist warns.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City in their majority were covered by a flexible pavement, composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the layer of asphalt, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that forms the layer, he said, is bathed an asphalt.
When vehicles pass through them by exerting effort, the vehicle allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would spread better, the chemical engineer said.
On the layer of asphalt, he said, we put a last layer called rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion on the street.
As the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the efforts, the rolling layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material it is made must be treated.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, it says, because they significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil becomes wet, the water spreads inside the layer, it is difficult for it to get out, which collapses all layers of the pavement and therefore causes the cracks.
In the process of forming a cassis, he said, the first that is damaged is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that needs to be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Searcher System explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of cassis and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be linked to the load of vehicles and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent formation of cassis.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on the asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow for easy and without having to use high temperatures.
