Japan was reborn after the earthquake
GDP increases by 1.5% through domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral in early March
Since March, Japan's economy had been paralyzed, which was still overwhelming after the devastating earthquake that had become a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster in the country of Japan since World War II.
The first estimates of the Government of Tokyo estimated the material losses at $300 billion, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seemed to have diminished.
After three consecutive trimesters of falls, the data of the Gross Domestic Product between July and September used to permanently rotate the page: GDP increased 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% at annual rate.
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year starts in March 2012 - also assumes the highest rate of increase from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of acquisitions of equipment to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investment by 1.1%, compared with the decrease of 0.9% of the capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of unabated increase.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based solely on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - infrastructures, use deficits for zero growth.
Japan has mainly woken up by changing domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by increased expenditure on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo has returned to the internal market when the yen - the Japanese currency - has become one of the "refugees" elected by investors who flee the eurozone debt crisis and the disturbances of the United States forecasts, a privilege that weighs like a slip in the accounts of the exporting companies.
With a stronger division, products are more expensive abroad, a serious reverse for a country whose economic float line is determined by the health of large technological groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, have been responsible for their low results between July and September for the contribution of yen.
While markets continue to occupy their seats in the peripheral countries of the EU, the Government of Yoshihiko Noda does not lower custody.
"The risks that persist, such as the deterioration of certain foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said the Secretary of State for Economic Policy, Motohisa Furukawa.
And indeed, prospects are not at all encouraging.
The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) noted that the majority of member countries presented clearer signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the turning points of the world economy has highlighted that the main powers are being curbed.
For it has dropped four decimal points to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 points out.
Eurozone was even below the average, which is at level 100, with eight decimal points down to 99.13 points.
