Euthanasia and assisted suicide must be legalized, says an expert committee
Canadians live in denial of death, according to the Royal Society of Canada's report
In the area of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and doctors to work together to ensure better palliative care, beyond cancer.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk to their doctor about the conditions under which they want to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the findings of a compelling report by the Royal Society of Canada, involving six experts from various areas, including ethics, law and medicine.
This committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code so as to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, where necessary, with a patient deemed competent to make such a decision.
At the start of the game, experts cite a recent survey of the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries on the planet.
If Canada has ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death."
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, report to us the experts commissioned by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the desire that most Canadians die at home, 68.6% end up dying at the hospital.
Overall, in Quebec, this rate is the highest, with 86% of the deaths occurring in the hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that are contrary to the position of the federal government, which has already said that they do not want to change anything in the Criminal Code regarding euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to experts, who have also reviewed all countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that such decriminalization leads to abuse in the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or suicide assisted by non-competent or non-consensive persons.
On the contrary, yesterday in teleconference Jocelyn Downie, co-signator of the report, there would be more cases of these overflows specifically in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasy is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"Assistance suicide is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," says Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in Euthanasia
Recall that 85% of Canadians have already voted in favour of euthanasia because they believe it would allow people in the end of life to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not have the effect of sending the message that the lives of the elderly or disabled have less value.
As for persons who have committed assisted suicide, the polls estimate 41 per cent that they should not be prosecuted.
With regard to the maintenance or cessation of care with a patient, the situation is less clear, the authors of the report say.
Therefore, in the list of their recommendations, they suggest that it is indicated in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of care for which there has been a legally valid refusal is not criminal.
The Committee of Experts also calls for health professionals to be trained in the duty to respect end-of-life care refusal without fear of criminal prosecution.
In the area of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and doctors to work together to ensure better palliative care, beyond cancer.
Finally, in terms of palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee requests that it be considered, when not used to reduce physical pain, such as euthanasia, and subject to the same procedures.
Other experts' reservations
Some experts in the field of health law have already made reservations regarding the findings of the Royal Society of Canada's report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, has described the position of the signatory experts of the report as "extreme" because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to the terminally ill.
"It opens the door to a situation where everyone who would be tired of life and who would be over 18 could ask for help to commit suicide," said Me Deschamps, who had consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
Mr Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report appear to place the person's autonomy above all other values that participate in the social fabric of society.
