The North Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream pipeline, directly connecting Western Europe to Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with a burst.
More than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated last Tuesday on the Baltic shores, between orchestra and fine buffet, at the inauguration of the North Stream, this new gas pipeline that connects Russia directly under the sea to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned together the valve steering the Russian gas entry into the western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe by a first 1 224 km tube connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Poranie.
A second tube must be completed at the end of 2012, enabling a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And the possibility of building a third on the same course is already mentioned.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge construction site has airs of victory.
The project had been strongly challenged by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The North Stream will actually allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries suddenly lose some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the North Stream to a "new German-Soviet Pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security from its supplies.
But it is at the price of a weakening Europe of energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has learned to win its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, heavily gas consumers, and whose deposits are declining.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us in an organic way," confirmed François Fillon by opening this pipeline, demonstrating to what extent major gas contracts are as political as economic.
All of this explains the broad smiles displayed by Gazprom leaders, present in numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical operation.
The submarine tube is made of concrete-gained steel to protect it against ship anchorages.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mine fields dating from the Second World War.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed, by caution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for North Stream.
There was also a need to multiply measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, that nothing interrupts throughout its length: no valve, no maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but project managers gave up while the Swedish were reluctant to see a Russian state society established permanently off their shores.
"In case of damage, we stop the passage of gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the gas pipeline shall therefore escape into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who planned the welds to get a leak every 100,000 years.
Monitoring of the state of the pipeline is carried out by an underwater robot, driven by a vessel, for external observation, as well as by an aircraft operating inside the pipeline.
In the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, width of one meter in diameter, and is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters second, it provides accurate information on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline was designed to run fifty years without having to undergo any repair.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
It's 200 bars at the start, and 100 on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, who keeps 51% of the shares.
Germans E.ON and BASF were joined (15.5% each), as well as Dutch Gasunie and French GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
She has her seat in Zoug, Switzerland, where the tax is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company, for twenty renewable years, all gas transport capabilities.
" Gazprom will pay for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Funding for gas pipeline construction was provided to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their expenses, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy pine-planted coast.
Valves, 4.5 meters tall, form the gas outlet.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that arrives before it is transferred to German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million an hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand name card.
Created some fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to re-enjoy the taste of writing.
He has a scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a broken white colour, as old as time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Mode, based in Milan, decided to launch a design notebook but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, is responsible for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin (skin skin) which means a varnished cotton used to cover banquets for example.
This type of booklet was very popular with writers and travelers.
" Moleskine gave the taste of the day an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of the avant-garde artists, up to the twentieth century " , says Maria Sebregondi, who became the brand leader at Mode.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million pieces.
We are far from the confidential production of the first few years, where only 3,000 books were designed.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish a robot portrait of the buyer, as the notebook seduces both the businessman and the student and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees at its beginnings, accounts for almost 100 today and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in the bookstores, from Fnac to small downtown shops and has been able to impose her identity.
"We have followed the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the e-mail rise," explains Maria Sebregondi.
