In August, she also launched a leopard cover on the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and its cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agenda, pens, computer covers... The brand runs on a wide range of media.
A success that made enemies: in the fall of 2006, Mode Mode was redeemed by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain so high?
About 19% of persons with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled people is open today.
Despite a voluntary public policy in 2005, the unemployment rate of persons with disabilities is even twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the whole population.
Discouragement?
"No, says Éric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled. "
" Progress over the past 15 years has been considerable. "
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
"However, there is still a great deal to be done. "
It must be said that for unemployed persons with disabilities, there are still many barriers to access to employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the scholarship and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for people with disabilities, compared to 38% on average.
In short, so many criteria that specifically complicate return to employment, and which "are the core of the problem," according to Christian Grapin, director general of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
This is for objective brakes.
It remains the non-dict, the mindset that evolves, of course, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entrepreneur for the City association indicated that the managers interviewed have "a low level of knowledge of disability ", with a "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, psychic or intellectual deficiencies ".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set out in a law of... 1987.
The last known figures, which date back to 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," said Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting the contributions of companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses," explained Pierre Blanc.
" But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of the institutions from 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of the enterprises from 100 to 199 employees.
